<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-461-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 461 802.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 22 1990 v7 n20 p41(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Turnkey network brings DOS, Unix together. (M 87 HCXZ Solutionturnkey DOS/Unix local area network) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrissey, Jane.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   M 87 (product introduction).andO;Product:   M 87 HCXZ Solution (Local area network) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Turnkey SystemsLocal Area NetworksProduct IntroductionMultitaskingOffice Automation Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Jane MorrisseyandM;Users who need a networked system that runs DOS and Unix applicationssimultaneously may find relief in a new turnkey network from M 87.andM;Called The HCXZ Solution, the multiuser, multitasking system allows as manyas 32 users to connect to and share the processing of a 386-based machine.andO;The software differs from traditional DOS-based multiuser systems such asAlloy Computer Products Inc.'s 386/Multiware because it is bundled with UnixSystem V to bring Unix workstations into the fold, M 87 officials claim.andP;  Theoperating environment also includes office-automation software, ispreconfigured for as many as 16 users and can work with a variety of PCs,workstations and terminals, they said.andM;Shipped last month, The HCXZ Solution is also being positioned againstfull-blown network operating systems such as Novell Inc.'s NetWare, accordingto James Cadell, product marketing director at M 87.andP;  The system allows usersto share data and applications as if on a LAN, but does not require users tobuy network-specific applications, a dedicated file server or networkadapters, officials said.andM;The center of the system is a 386-based, 25MHz computer developed by M 87that comes with 4M bytes of memory, a 160M-byte hard drive, a 2400-bps modemand an uninterruptible power supply.andP;  Workstations attach to the host portsvia standard telephone wire connected to communication ports.andM;The system includes Unix System V and a suite of Unix-based officeapplications, called the Goldmedal Office Automation System, which M 87licenses from Decathlon Data Systems Inc..andP;  The package offersword-processing, graphics, relational-database, electronic-mail andpersonal-productivity programs under one interface.andM;An eight-user system, including system software, Goldmedal applications andthe 386 server, costs $12,500.andP;  A 16-user system costs $14,500.andP;  M 87engineers will install the system, and the company offers six hours of freetelephone support.andM;M 87, of Medinah, Ill., can be reached at (800) 447-8649.andO;</TEXT></DOC>